id="post-2341" class="post-2341 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-environment tag-africa tag-conservation tag-fence tag-kenya tag-nairobi tag-protection tag-rhino-ark tag-water"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2010/03/01/one-amazing-fence/" title="Permalink to One Amazing Fence" rel="bookmark">One Amazing Fence</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2010/03/01 10:15 am"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2010/03/01/one-amazing-fence/" title="One Amazing Fence" rel="bookmark">2010/03/01 10:15 am</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>Fences can build good neighbours and fences can save the environment. One fence has done<br
/> wonders for protecting rhinos and water.</p><blockquote><p>Colin Church, the chair of the Kenya-based Rhino Ark conservation group and a leading expert on African leading wildlife, said the fence, which took 21 years for local communities to complete, had failed to save the rhino in the uplands it surrounds.</p><p>However, it had succeeded in protecting a large forest area and the sources of four of seven of Kenya&#8217;s largest rivers, all of which rise in the Aberdares and provide electricity and water to major cities including Nairobi.</p><p>&#8220;In the early days, the motivation was to protect the black rhino, but then we all woke up to the fact that the farmers [who lived near the fence] were celebrating, and the reality is that this forested mountain area was the lifeblood for millions of people. We realised the whole ecosystem was at stake,&#8221; he said.</p><p>&#8220;Our thinking had to change.The Aberdares are now the most secure mountain ecosystem in the whole of Kenya and maybe Africa.&#8221;</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2010/feb/28/kenya-fence-water-sources-rivers">Keep reading at The Guardian.</a></p><div
class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-1111807-2341-53848c76ee62d' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/#blog_id=1111807&amp;post_id=2341&amp;origin=www.thingsaregood.com&amp;obj_id=1111807-2341-53848c76ee62d' data-name='like-post-frame-1111807-2341-53848c76ee62d'><h3 class='sd-title'>Like this:</h3><div
